Question 1 Background

rural_development_data is an extract from USDA Rural Developmentâs dashboard found on https://www.rd.usda.gov/rural-data-gateway/rural-investments

fiscal_year is the fiscal year, ranges from 2012-2024 (Note: 2024 is only partial data)

state_name includes the state name or territory name

program_area is the USDA program area that made the investment (Business Programs, Community Facilities, Electric Programs, Multifamily Housing, Single Family Housing, Telecommunications Programs, Water and Environmental)

number_investments is the total investment counts made by Rural Development (one of USDAâs agencies)

svi_investments is the total USDA investment that went towards communities that are considered socially vulnerable

Question 5.a. Background Information

The cancer_atlas.xlsx data is a data extract from the World Health Organization (WHO)âs Global Cancer Observatory data. The detailed variable documentation for this partial data is as follows:

state: state, country, or territory with data, whether partial or full.

iso3_code: three-letter country codes defined in ISO 3166-1

alcohol_cancer_death: Cancer deaths attributable to alcohol. Proportion (%) of cancer deaths caused by alcohol drinking in men ages 15 years or older, 2016.

smoking_prevalence_male: Smoking prevalence male. Prevalence (%) of daily smoking for men.

smoking_prevalence_female: Smoking prevalence female. Prevalence (%) of daily smoking for women.

obesity_prevalence_male: Obesity prevalence male for 2016.

obesity_prevalence_female: Obesity prevalence female for 2016.

lung_cancer_incidence_male: Lung cancer incidence rates, male Age-standardized rate (world) per 100,000, all ages, 2018.

lung_cancer_incidence_female: Lung cancer incidence rates, female Age-standardized rate (world) per 100,000, all ages, 2018.

most_common_female_cancer_case: Most common cancer type in the country for females (in 2018) (e.g., Breast, Kaposi sarcoma)

most_common_female_cancer_death: Most common cancer type deaths in the country for females (in 2018) (e.g., Breast, Kaposi sarcoma)

most_common_male_cancer_case: Most common cancer type in the country for males (in 2018) (e.g., Breast, Kaposi sarcoma)

most_common_male_cancer_death: Most common cancer type deaths in the country for males (in 2018) (e.g., Breast, Kaposi sarcoma)

  • patient_id is the unique patient identifier for the clinical trial participant

  • drug is the active ingredient (Drug AZ1Q29, Semaglutide, Tirzepatide)

  • sex is the assigned sex at birth

  • percent_weight_loss is the % of total weight loss after a year of taking the drug.

Suppose you are interesting in studying the most popular plane models that flew in and out of NYC airports. However, the flights table do not contain model information about the planes. But another table called planes does! More specifically, planes contain a model variable/column that you are interested in. Using the R chunk below, perform the appropriate join to supplement flights with data from planes to ensure your new data frame contains the model variable/columnâmake sure to use tailnum as the join key. You may think of tailnum as the aircraft registration number.

For this problem, you may want to use the help pane to read more about planes and its variables.

Save the resulting table or data frame as flights_v2 in your R envât.

flights_v2 <- flights |>
